Schools\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (school talent shows, high school dances)\nActivity = DeclareSort(\"Activity\")  # Activities (performing in school talent shows, chaperoning high school dances)\n\n# Define predicates\nAttends = Function(\"Attends\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # Attends(x, s)\nIs_Engaged = Function(\"Is_Engaged\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # IsEngaged(x, s)\nIs_Inactive = Function(\"Is_Inactive\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsInactive(x)\nIs_Interested = Function(\"Is_Interested\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsInterested(x)\nChaperones = Function(\"Chaperones\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # Chaperones(x, e)\nWishes_To_Further = Function(\"Wishes_To_Further\", Person, BoolSort())  # WishesToFurther(x)\nIs_Student = Function(\"Is_Student\", Person, School, BoolSort())  # IsStudent(x, s)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ns = Const(\"s\", School)\ne = Const(\"e\", Event)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(And(Is_In(x), Attends(x, s)), Is_Engaged(x, s)))  # \u2200x (In(x) \u2192 Attends(x, s) \u2192 Engaged(x, s))\nsolver.add(Or(Attends(x, s), And(Is_Inactive(x), Not(Is_Interested(x))))  # \u2200x (In(x) \u2228 (Inactive(x) \u2227 \u00acInterested(x)))\nsolver.add(Not(And(Chaperones(x, e), Is_Student(x, s)))  # \u2200x (Student(x, s) \u2227 Young(x) \u2227 Teenager(x) \u2192 WishesToFurther(x) \u2192 Student(x, s))\nsolver.add(Is_Young(Bonnie))  # Young(Bonnie)\nsolver.add(Is_Teenager(Bonnie))  # Teenager(Bonnie)\nsolver.add(Or(And(Attends(Bonnie, s), Is_Engaged(Bonnie, s)), Not(And(Attends(Bonnie, s), Not(Is_Student(Bonnie, s)))))  # Bonnie \u2208 In(x) \u2227 Engaged(x, s) \u2228 \u00ac(In(x) \u2227 \u00acStudent(x, s))\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Attends(Bonnie, s)  # Bonnie performs in school talent shows often\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Bonnie performs in school talent shows often. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Bonnie does not perform in school talent shows often. IsChild(x)\nIs_Teenager = Function(\"Is_Teenager\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsTeenager(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\nschool = Const(\"school\", School)\nevent = Const(\"event\", School_Event)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(IsIn(x, \"the club\"), Attends(x, school)), And(Is_Engaged(x, school), Is_Engaged(x, school))))  # Bonnie is either both attends and is very engaged with school events or is not someone who both attends and is very engaged with school events.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(Or(And(IsChild(Bonnie), IsTeenager(Bonnie), Wishes_To_Further(Bonnie), Chaperones(Bonnie, event)), Not(And(IsChild(Bonnie), IsTeenager(Bonnie), Wishes_To_Further(Bonnie))), Or(IsStudent(Bonnie, school), IsInactive(Bonnie)))\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  #         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # People\nSchool = DeclareSort(\"School\")  # Schools\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_In_Club = Function(\"Is_In_Club\", Person, BoolSort())  # InThisClub(x)\nIs_Student = Function(\"Is_Student\", Person, BoolSort())  # Student(x)\nAttends_School = Function(\"Attends_School\", Person, BoolSort())  # Attends(x, school)\nIs_Engaged = Function(\"Is_Engaged\", Person, BoolSort())  # Engaged(x)\nIs_Inactive = Function(\"Is_Inactive\", Person, BoolSort())  # Inactive(x)\nIs_Interested = Function(\"Is_Interested\", Person, BoolSort())  # Interested(x)\nChaperones = Function(\"Chaperones\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # Chaperones(x, event)\nPerforms_TalentShow = Function(\"Performs_TalentShow\", Person, BoolSort())  # PerformsInTalentShow(x)\nWishes_To_Further_Academic_Career = Function(\"Wishes_To_Further_Academic_Career\", Person, BoolSort())  # WishesToFurtherCareer(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBonnie = Const(\"Bonnie\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ns = Const(\"s\", School)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_In_Club(Bonnie), And(Performs_TalentShow(Bonnie), Is_Engaged(Bonnie)))  # \u2200x (InThisClub(x) \u2192 (PerformsInTalentShow(x) \u2227 Engaged(x)))\nsolver.add(Or(Performs_TalentShow(Bonnie), And(Is_Inactive(Bonnie), Not(Is_Interested(Bonnie))))  # \u2200x (InThisClub(x) \u2192 (PerformsInTalentShow(x) \u2228 (Inactive(x) \u2227 \u00acInterested(x)))\nsolver.add(Not(And(Is_Student(Bonnie), Chaperones(Bonnie, s)))  # \u2200x (Student(x) \u2192 (Engaged(x) \u2227 Attends(x, school)))\nsolver.add(Wishes_To_Further_Academic_Career(Bonnie)  # WishesToFurtherCareer(bonnie)\nsolver.add(Or(And(Attends_School(Bonnie), Is_Engaged(Bonnie)), Not(And(Attends_School(Bonnie), Is_Engaged(Bonnie)))  # (Attends(bonnie, school) \u2227 Engaged(bonnie)) \u2228 (\u00acAttends(bonnie, school) \u2227 \u00acEngaged(bonnie))\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(Or(Chaperones(Bonnie, s), Not(Chaperones(Bonnie, s)), And(Wishes_To_Further_Academic_Career(Bonnie), Is_Inactive(Bonnie)))  # (Chaperones(bonnie, school) \u2228 \u00acChaperones(bonnie, school)) \u2192 (WishesToFurtherCareer(bonnie) \u2227 Inactive(bonnie))\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # (True)\")\n    print(\"The final answer is True.\")\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: If Bonnie either chaperones high school dances or, if she does not, she performs in school talent shows often, then Bonnie is both a young child or teenager who wishes to further her academic career and educational opportunities and an inactive and disinterested member of the community. (False)\")\n    print(\"The final answer is False.\")\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    -         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # People (Employees)\nLocation = DeclareSort(\"Location\")  # Places (Company Building, Home, Other Countries)\nPosition = DeclareSort(\"Position\")  # Job Positions (Manager, Non-Manager)\n\n# Define predicates\nScheduledMeeting = Function(\"ScheduledMeeting\", Person, Person, BoolSort())  # Scheduled(x, y)\nHasLunch = Function(\"HasLunch\", Person, Location, BoolSort())  # HasLunch(x, location)\nWorksFrom = Function(\"WorksFrom\", Person, Location, BoolSort())  # WorksFrom(x, location)\nInCountry = Function(\"InCountry\", Person, BoolSort())  # InCountry(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nJames = Const(\"James\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(ScheduledMeeting(x, x), HasLunch(x, Location(\"CompanyBuilding\"))))  # \u2200x (Scheduled(x, x) \u2192 HasLunch(x, CompanyBuilding))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(HasLunch(x, Location(\"CompanyBuilding\")), ScheduledMeeting(x, x))))  # \u2200x (HasLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) \u2192 Scheduled(x, x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Or(HasLunch(x, Location(\"CompanyBuilding\")), HasLunch(x, Location(\"Home\"))))  # \u2200x (HasLunch(x, CompanyBuilding) \u2228 HasLunch(x, Home))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(HasLunch(x, Location(\"Home\")), WorksFrom(x, Location(\"Home\"))))  # \u2200x (HasLunch(x, Home) \u2192 WorksFrom(x, Home))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(InCountry(x), WorksFrom(x, Location(\"OtherCountries\"))))  # \u2200x (InCountry(x) \u2192 WorksFrom(x, OtherCountries))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Not(WorksFrom(x, Location(\"Home\"))), Not(InCountry(x))))  # \u2200x (\u00acWorksFrom(x, Home) \u2192 \u00acInCountry(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Manager(x), Location(\"CompanyBuilding\") == Location(\"CompanyBuilding\")))  # \u2200x (Manager(x) \u2227 CompanyBuilding = CompanyBuilding \u2192 CompanyBuilding = CompanyBuilding)\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Not(Location(\"CompanyBuilding\") == Location(\"CompanyBuilding\")), Not(Manager(x))), Not(Location(\"CompanyBuilding\") == Location(\"CompanyBuilding\"))))  # Beings (e.g., Humans, Animals)\nSymptom = DeclareSort(\"Symptom\")  # Symptoms (e.g., Fever, Headache)\n\n# Define predicates\nHas_Virus = Function(\"Has_Virus\", Being, Virus, BoolSort())  # Virus(x, being)\nIs_Animal = Function(\"Is_Animal\", Being, BoolSort())  # Animal(x)\nIs_Mammal = Function(\"Is_Mammal\", Being, BoolSort())  # Mammal(x)\nIs_Monkeypox = Function(\"Is_Monkeypox\", Virus, BoolSort())  # Monkeypox(x)\nHas_Symptom = Function(\"Has_Symptom\", Being, Symptom, BoolSort())  # Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Types of wild turkeys (Eastern, Osceola, Gould\u2019s, Merriam\u2019s, Rio Grande, Ocellated)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsEasternWildTurkey = Function(\"IsEasternWildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # EasternWildTurkey(x)\nIsOsceolaWildTurkey = Function(\"IsOsceolaWildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # OsceolaWildTurkey(x)\nIsGouldsWildTurkey = Function(\"IsGouldsWildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # Gould\u2019sWildTurkey(x)\nIsMerriamsWildTurkey = Function(\"IsMerriamsWildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # OcellatedWildTurkey(x)\nIsWildTurkey = Function(\"IsWildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # WildTurkey(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nTom = Const(\"Tom\", Person)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Not(IsEasternWildTurkey(Tom)))  # \u00acEasternWildTurkey(Tom)\nsolver.add(Not(IsOsceolaWildTurkey(Tom)))  # \u00acOsceolaWildTurkey(Tom)\nsolver.add(Not(IsGouldsWildTurkey(Tom)))  # \u00acGould\u2019sWildTurkey(Tom)\nsolver.add(Or(Not(IsMerriamsWildTurkey(Tom)), Not(IsRioGrandeWildTurkey(Tom))))  # \u00ac(Merriam\u2019sWildTurkey(Tom) \u2228 RioGrandeWildTurkey(Tom))\nsolver.add(IsWildTurkey(Tom))  # WildTurkey(Tom)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = IsEasternWildTurkey(Tom)  # EasternWildTurkey(Tom)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Tom is an Eastern wild turkey. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Tom is not an Eastern wild turkey. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. Types of wild turkeys (Eastern, Osceola, Gould\u2019s, Merriam\u2019s, Rio Grande, Ocellated)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Eastern = Function(\"Is_Eastern\", Person, BoolSort())  # Eastern(x)\nIs_Osceola = Function(\"Is_Osceola\", Person, BoolSort())  # Osceola(x)\nIs_Goulds = Function(\"Is_Goulds\", Person, BoolSort())  # Gould\u2019s(x)\nIs_Merriams = Function(\"Is_Merriams\", Person, BoolSort())  # Merriam\u2019s(x)\nIs_RioGrande = Function(\"Is_RioGrande\", Person, BoolSort())  # Rio Grande(x)\nIs_Ocellated = Function(\"Is_Ocellated\", Person, BoolSort())  # Ocellated(x)\nIs_WildTurkey = Function(\"Is_WildTurkey\", Person, BoolSort())  # WildTurkey(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nTom = Const(\"Tom\", Person)\nJoey = Const(\"Joey\", Person)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Eastern(Tom)))  # Tom is not an Eastern wild turkey\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Osceola(Tom)))  # Tom is not an Osceola wild turkey\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Goulds(Tom)))  # Tom is not a Gould's wild turkey\nsolver.add(Or(Not(Is_Merriams(Tom)), Not(Is_RioGrande(Tom))))  # A Japanese game company created the game the Legend of Zelda.\nsolver.add(Is_Japanese(The_Legend_Of_Zelda))  # All games on the Top 10 list are made by Japanese game companies.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Top10(x), Is_Japanese(x))))  # FIFA 22 is made by a Japanese video game company.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: FIFA 22 is made by a Japanese video game company. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: FIFA 22 is not made by a Japanese video game company. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Created(x, y)\nIs_In_List = Function(\"Is_In_List\", Game, List, BoolSort())  # In(x, y)\nSold_Copies = Function(\"Sold_Copies\", Game, BoolSort())  # SoldMoreThanOneMillion(x)\nIs_Top10 = Function(\"Is_Top10\", List, BoolSort())  # A Japanese game company created the game the Legend of Zelda.\nsolver.add(Created(A_Japanese_Game_Company, The_Legend_Of_Zelda))  # All games on the Top 10 list are made by Japanese game companies.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_In_List(x, The_Top10_List), Is_Japanese(A_Japanese_Game_Company))))  # Places (Campus)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_SpottedNearCampus = Function(\"Is_SpottedNearCampus\", Animal, BoolSort())  # SpottedNear(x, campus)\nIs_Cute = Function(\"Is_Cute\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cute(x)\nIs_Skittish = Function(\"Is_Skittish\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Skittish(x)\nIs_Calm = Function(\"Is_Calm\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Calm(x)\nIs_Rabbit = Function(\"Is_Rabbit\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Rabbit(x)\nIs_Turtle = Function(\"Is_Turtle\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Turtle(x)\nIs_Squirrel = Function(\"Is_Squirrel\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Squirrel(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nRockie = Const(\"Rockie\", Animal)\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\ny = Const(\"y\", Location)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x), Is_Cute(x)))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, campus) \u2192 Cute(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x), Is_Turtle(x)))  # \u2203x (SpottedNear(x, campus) \u2227 Turtle(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x), Or(Is_Rabbit(x), Is_Squirrel(x))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, campus) \u2192 Rabbit(x) \u2228 Squirrel(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Skittish(x), Not(Is_Calm(x))))  # \u2200x (Skittish(x) \u2192 \u00acCalm(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x), Is_Skittish(x))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNear(x, campus) \u2192 Skittish(x))\nsolver.add(Is_Calm(Rockie))  # Calm(Rockie)\nsolver.add(Is_SpottedNearCampus(Rockie))  # SpottedNear(Rockie, campus)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Is_Turtle(Rockie))  # \u00acTurtle(Rockie)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Rockie is not a turtle. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Rockie is a turtle. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

**Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Places (Campus)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_SpottedNearCampus = Function(\"Is_SpottedNearCampus\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Spotted(x, nearCampus)\nIs_Cute = Function(\"Is_Cute\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cute(x)\nIs_Skittish = Function(\"Is_Skittish\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Skittish(x)\nIs_Calm = Function(\"Is_Calm\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Calm(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nRockie = Const(\"Rockie\", Animal)\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\ny = Const(\"y\", Animal)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_SpottedNearCampus(x), Is_Cute(x)))  # (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Rockie is neither a turtle nor cute. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions.         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nAnimal = DeclareSort(\"Animal\")  # Animals (Rabbits, Turtles, Squirrels)\nLocation = DeclareSort(\"Location\")  # Locations (Campus)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Spotted_Near_Campus = Function(\"Is_Spotted_Near_Campus\", Animal, BoolSort())  # SpottedNearCampus(x)\nIs_Cute = Function(\"Is_Cute\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Cute(x)\nIs_Skittish = Function(\"Is_Skittish\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Skittish(x)\nIs_Calm = Function(\"Is_Calm\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Calm(x)\nIs_Rabbit = Function(\"Is_Rabbit\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Rabbit(x)\nIs_Turtle = Function(\"Is_Turtle\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Turtle(x)\nIs_Squirrel = Function(\"Is_Squirrel\", Animal, BoolSort())  # Squirrel(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nRockie = Const(\"Rockie\", Animal)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Animal)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Spotted_Near_Campus(x), Is_Cute(x))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2192 Cute(x))\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(Is_Spotted_Near_Campus(x), Is_Turtle(x))))  # \u2203x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2227 Turtle(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Spotted_Near_Campus(x), Or(Is_Rabbit(x), Is_Squirrel(x)))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2192 Rabbit(x) \u2228 Squirrel(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Skittish(x), Not(Is_Calm(x)))))  # \u2200x (Skittish(x) \u2192 \u00acCalm(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Spotted_Near_Campus(x), Is_Skittish(x))))  # \u2200x (SpottedNearCampus(x) \u2192 Skittish(x))\nsolver.add(Is_Spotted_Near_Campus(Rockie))  # SpottedNearCampus(Rockie)\nsolver.add(Is_Calm(Rockie))  # Calm(Rockie)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Implies(And(Is_Cute(Rockie), Is_Calm(Rockie)), Is_Skittish(Rockie))  # Cute(Rockie) \u2227 Calm(Rockie) \u2192 Skittish(Rockie)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: If Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is a skittish turtle. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: If Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is not a skittish turtle. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions.                 "content": "You are an AI assistant that generates Python code for logical reasoning using the Z3 SMT solver. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - The Python Code should be enclosed within <PYTHON> and </PYTHON>.\n\nYou need to understand the aformentioned rules before generating the codes.\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<Premises>\nAll rabbits that can be spotted near the campus are cute. \nSome turtles can be spotted near the campus. \nThe only animals that can be spotted near the campus are rabbits and squirrels.\nIf something is skittish, then it is not calm.\nAll the squirrels that can be spotted near the campus are skittish.\nRockie can be spotted near the campus, and it is calm.\n</Premises>\n<Conclusion>\nIf Rockie is cute and calm, then Rockie is a skittish turtle.\n</Conclusion>\n<PYTHON>\n"

People (Karen, Lisa)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Popular = Function(\"Is_Popular\", Show, BoolSort())  # Popular(x)\nIs_BingeWatched = Function(\"Is_BingeWatched\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # BingeWatched(x, y)\nIs_Downloaded = Function(\"Is_Downloaded\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # Downloaded(x, y)\nIs_Shared = Function(\"Is_Shared\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # Shared(x, y)\nIs_Netflix = Function(\"Is_Netflix\", Show, BoolSort())  # Netflix(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nStranger_Things = Const(\"Stranger_Things\", Show)\nBlack_Mirror = Const(\"Black_Mirror\", Show)\nKaren = Const(\"Karen\", Person)\nLisa = Const(\"Lisa\", Person)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Show)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Popular(Stranger_Things))  # Stranger Things is popular\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Popular(x), Is_BingeWatched(Karen, x)))  # If a show is popular, Karen will binge-watch it\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_BingeWatched(Karen, x), Is_Downloaded(Karen, x))))  # BingeWatches(x, y)\nDownloads = Function(\"Downloads\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # Downloads(x, y)\nIs_Netflix = Function(\"Is_Netflix\", Show, BoolSort())  # IsNetflix(x)\nShared = Function(\"Shared\", Person, Show, BoolSort())  # HostedParalympics(x)\nRanked_High = Function(\"Ranked_High\", University, BoolSort())  # RankedHigh(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBeijing = Const(\"Beijing\", City)\nChina = Const(\"China\", Country)\nThe_World = Const(\"The_World\", Country)\nx = Const(\"x\", City)\ny = Const(\"y\", University)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Capital(Beijing, China))  # Beijing is the capital of China\nsolver.add(Is_Populous(China))  # China is the most populous nation\nsolver.add(Is_Located_In(Beijing, China))  # Beijing is located in China\nsolver.add(Hosted_Olympics(Beijing))  # Beijing hosted the 2008 Summer Olympics\nsolver.add(Hosted_Paralympics(Beijing))  # Beijing hosted the 2008 Summer Paralympics\nsolver.add(Exists([x], And(Hosted_Olympics(x), Hosted_Paralympics(x))))  # Beijing hosted both Summer and Winter Olympics\nsolver.add(Exists([y], Ranked_High(y)))  # Many universities in Beijing are ranked high\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Or(Hosted_Olympics(Beijing), Hosted_Olympics(Beijing))  # Beijing hosted both the 2008 Summer Olympics and the Winter Olympics\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Beijing hosted both the 2008 Summer Olympics and the Winter Olympics. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Beijing did not host both the 2008 Summer Olympics and the Winter Olympics. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Countries\nRegion = DeclareSort(\"Region\")  # Regions\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Capital = Function(\"Is_Capital\", Country, City, BoolSort())  # Capital(x, y)\nIs_Located_In = Function(\"Is_Located_In\", City, Region, BoolSort())  # LocatedIn(x, y)\nIs_Populous = Function(\"Is_Populous\", Country, BoolSort())  # Populous(x)\nHosted_Olympics = Function(\"Hosted_Olympics\", City, BoolSort())  # HostedOlympics(x)\nHas_Universities = Function(\"Has_Universities\", City, BoolSort())  # HasUniversities(x)\nRanked_High = Function(\"Ranked_High\", City, BoolSort())  # RankedHigh(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBeijing = Const(\"Beijing\", City)\nChina = Const(\"China\", Country)\nNorthern_China = Const(\"Northern_China\", Region)\nSouthern_China = Const(\"Southern_China\", Region)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", City)\ny = Const(\"y\", Country)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Capital(China, Beijing))  # Beijing is the capital of China\nsolver.add(Is_Capital(Beijing, x))  # Beijing is the capital of the world's most populous nation\nsolver.add(Is_Located_In(Beijing, Northern_China))  # Beijing is located in Northern China\nsolver.add(Hosted_Olympics(Beijing))  # (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Beijing is not located in southern China. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. University\nNation = DeclareSort(\"Nation\")  # Nation\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Capital = Function(\"Is_Capital\", City, Nation, BoolSort())  # Capital(x, y)\nIs_Located_In = Function(\"Is_Located_In\", City, BoolSort())  # LocatedIn(x)\nIs_Populous = Function(\"Is_Populous\", Nation, BoolSort())  # Populous(y)\nHosted = Function(\"Hosted\", City, BoolSort())  # Hosted(x, event)\nRanked = Function(\"Ranked\", University, BoolSort())  # Ranked(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nBeijing = Const(\"Beijing\", City)\nChina = Const(\"China\", Nation)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", City)\ny = Const(\"y\", Nation)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_Capital(Beijing, China))  # Beijing is the capital of the People's Republic of China\nsolver.add(Is_Capital(Beijing, x))  # Beijing is the capital city of the world's most populous nation\nsolver.add(Is_Located_In(Beijing))  # Beijing is located in Northern China\nsolver.add(Hosted(Beijing))  # Planets (Earth, Mars)\nAttribute = DeclareSort(\"Attribute\")  # Attributes (intelligence, being_from_Earth, being_from_Mars)\n\n# Define predicates\nIsAlien = Function(\"IsAlien\", Person, BoolSort())  # FromMars(x)\nIsHighlyIntelligent = Function(\"IsHighlyIntelligent\", Person, BoolSort())  # HighlyIntelligent(x)\nIsHuman = Function(\"IsHuman\", Person, BoolSort())  # Human(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nMarvin = Const(\"Marvin\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Planet)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsAlien(x), IsExtraterrestrial(x)))  # \u2200x (Alien(x) \u2192 Extraterrestrial(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(FromMars(x), IsAlien(x))))  # \u2200x (FromMars(x) \u2192 Alien(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsExtraterrestrial(x), Not(IsHuman(x))))  # \u2200x (Extraterrestrial(x) \u2192 \u00acHuman(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsHighlyIntelligent(x) And FromEarth(x), IsHuman(x))))  # \u2200x (HighlyIntelligent(x) \u2227 FromEarth(x) \u2192 Human(x))\nsolver.add(IsHighlyIntelligent(Marvin))  # Everyone at the mixer is a Grand Slam champion or an Oscar-nominated actor.\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_GrandSlamChampion(x), Is_ProfessionalTennisPlayer(x)))  # Every Grand Slam champion at the mixer is a professional tennis player.\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_OscarNominatedActor(x), Is_Celebrity(x)))  # All Oscar-nominated actors at the mixer are celebrities.\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_ProfessionalTennisPlayer(x), Is_Athlete(x)))  # All professional tennis players at the mixer are athletes.\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Celebrity(x), Is_WellPaid(x)))  # If a person at the mixer is a celebrity, then they are well paid.\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Athlete(x), Is_Famous(x)))  # If a person at the mixer is an athlete, then they are famous.\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_WellPaid(x), LivesInTaxHaven(x))))  # All well-paid people at the mixer live in tax havens.\nsolver.add(Is_GrandSlamChampion(Djokovic))  # Djokovic is a Grand Slam champion\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Famous(Djokovic), Is_WellPaid(Djokovic)))  # If Djokovic is a famous athlete, then Djokovic is well-paid.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = LivesInTaxHaven(Djokovic)  # Djokovic lives in a tax haven.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Djokovic lives in a tax haven. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Djokovic does not live in a tax haven. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - The Python Code should be enclosed within <PYTHON> and </PYTHON>.\n\nYou need to understand the aformentioned rules before generating the codes.\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<Premises>\nEveryone at the mixer is a Grand Slam champion or an Oscar-nominated actor.\nEvery Grand Slam champion at the mixer is a professional tennis player.\nAll Oscar-nominated actors at the mixer are celebrities.\nAll professional tennis players at the mixer are athletes.\nIf a person at the mixer is a celebrity, then they are well paid.\nIf a person at the mixer is an athlete, then they are famous.\nAll well-paid people at the mixer live in tax havens.\nDjokovic is at the mixer: if Djokovic is a famous athlete, then Djokovic is well-paid.\n</Premises>\n<Conclusion>\nDjokovic lives in a tax haven.\n</Conclusion>\n<PYTHON>\n"

Places (the mixer)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Grand_Slam_Champion = Function(\"Is_Grand_Slam_Champion\", Person, BoolSort())  # GrandSlamChampion(x)\nIs_Oscars_Nominated = Function(\"Is_Oscars_Nominated\", Person, BoolSort())  # OscarsNominated(x)\nIs_Professional_Tennis_Player = Function(\"Is_Professional_Tennis_Player\", Person, BoolSort())  # ProfessionalTennisPlayer(x)\nIs_Celebrity = Function(\"Is_Celebrity\", Person, BoolSort())  # Famous(x)\nLives_In_Tax_Haven = Function(\"Lives_In_Tax_Haven\", Person, BoolSort())  # LivesInTaxHaven(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nDjokovic = Const(\"Djokovic\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Or(Is_Grand_Slam_Champion(x), Is_Oscars_Nominated(x)))  # \u2200x (AtTheMixer(x) \u2192 GrandSlamChampion(x) \u2228 OscarsNominated(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Grand_Slam_Champion(x), Is_Professional_Tennis_Player(x)))  # \u2200x (GrandSlamChampion(x) \u2192 ProfessionalTennisPlayer(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Oscars_Nominated(x), Is_Celebrity(x)))  # \u2200x (OscarsNominated(x) \u2192 Celebrity(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Professional_Tennis_Player(x), Is_Athlete(x)))  # \u2200x (ProfessionalTennisPlayer(x) \u2192 Athlete(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Celebrity(x), Is_Well_Paid(x)))  # \u2200x (Celebrity(x) \u2192 WellPaid(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_Athlete(x), Is_Famous(x)))  # \u2200x (Athlete(x) \u2192 Famous(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], And(Is_Well_Paid(x), Lives_In_Tax_Haven(x))))  # \u2200x (WellPaid(x) \u2192 LivesInTaxHaven(x))\nsolver.add(Is_Famous(Djokovic))  # Famous(Djokovic)\nsolver.add(Is_Athlete(Djokovic))  # Athlete(Djokovic)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Lives_In_Tax_Haven(Djokovic))  # \u00acLivesInTaxHaven(Djokovic)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Djokovic does not live in a tax haven. Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - Orchestras are led by conductors.\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(Is_Conductor(Beethoven))  # Beethoven is not a conductor.\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Beethoven is not a conductor. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Beethoven is a conductor. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - Evocative(x)\nIs_Dreamy = Function(\"Is_Dreamy\", DesignStyle, BoolSort())  # Dreamy(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nMax = Const(\"Max\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", DesignStyle)\ns = Const(\"s\", Building)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(And(Is_Zaha_Hadid_Design(x), Adores(Max, x), Has_Interesting_Geometries(x))))  #         "conclusions": "A design by Max is either evocative or dreamy.",
        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # Person\nBuilding = DeclareSort(\"Building\")  # Building\nStyle = DeclareSort(\"Style\")  # Style (Zaha Hadid's design style, Kelly Wearstler's design style)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Design_By = Function(\"Is_Design_By\", Person, Building, BoolSort())  # Design(x, y)\nIs_Style = Function(\"Is_Style\", Building, Style, BoolSort())  # Style(x, y)\nIs_Adores = Function(\"Is_Adores\", Person, Style, BoolSort())  # Adores(x, y)\nHas_Interesting_Geometries = Function(\"Has_Interesting_Geometries\", Building, BoolSort())  # InterestingGeometries(x)\nIs_Brutalist_Building = Function(\"Is_Brutalist_Building\", Building, BoolSort())  # BrutalistBuilding(x)\nIs_Evocative = Function(\"Is_Evocative\", Building, BoolSort())  # Evocative(x)\nIs_Dreamy = Function(\"Is_Dreamy\", Building, BoolSort())  # Dreamy(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nMax = Const(\"Max\", Person)\nZaha_Hadid = Const(\"Zaha_Hadid\", Person)\nKelly_Wearstler = Const(\"Kelly_Wearstler\", Person)\nThe_Design = Const(\"The_Design\", Building)\nThe_Style = Const(\"The_Style\", Style)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Building)\ny = Const(\"y\", Style)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Adores(Max, The_Style), Has_Interesting_Geometries(x))))  # \u2200x (Adores(Max, x) \u2192 InterestingGeometries(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Brutalist_Building(x), Not(Has_Interesting_Geometries(x))))  # \u2200x (BrutalistBuilding(x) \u2192 \u00acInterestingGeometries(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Or(Is_Style(x, The_Style), Or(Is_Design_By(Max, x))))  # \u2200x (Style(x) \u2228 Design(x, Max))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Adores(Max, x), And(Is_Evocative(x), Is_Dreamy(x))))  # \u2200x (Adores(Max, x) \u2192 Evocative(x) \u2227 Dreamy(x))\nsolver.add(Implies(And(Has_Interesting_Geometries(x), Is_Design_By(Max, x)), And(Is_Brutalist_Building(x), Is_Evocative(x))))  # (Design(x, Max) \u2227 InterestingGeometries(x)) \u2192 BrutalistBuilding(x) \u2227 Evocative(x)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Or(Is_Evocative(x), Is_Dreamy(x))  # Evocative(x) \u2228 Dreamy(x)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: A design by Max is either evocative or dreamy. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: A design by Max is neither evocative nor dreamy. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - At(x, t)\nIs_Most_Active = Function(\"Is_Most_Active\", Person, BoolSort())  # MostActive(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nCoco_Gauff = Const(\"Coco_Gauff\", Person)\nIga_Swi\u0105tek = Const(\"Iga_Swi\u0105tek\", Person)\nRafael_Nadal = Const(\"Rafael_Nadal\", Person)\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\nt = Const(\"t\", Tournament)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(Ranked_Highly_By_WTA(x), Is_Active_In_Major_Tennis(x)))  # Tennis players\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (Roland Garros 2022)\n\n# Define predicates\nRankedHighlyByWTA = Function(\"RankedHighlyByWTA\", Person, BoolSort())  # RankedHighlyByWTA(x)\nIsMostActiveInMajorTennis = Function(\"IsMostActiveInMajorTennis\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsMostActiveInMajorTennis(x)\nLostTo = Function(\"LostTo\", Person, Person, Event, BoolSort())  # LostTo(x, y, e)\nIsFemale = Function(\"IsFemale\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsFemale(x)\nIsMale = Function(\"IsMale\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsAt(Coco_Gauff, e)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = LostTo(Coco_Gauff, Rafael_Nadal, e)  # The conclusion to check\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Coco Gauff has lost to Rafael Nadal.         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nPerson = DeclareSort(\"Person\")  # People (Coco Gauff, Iga \u015awi\u0105tek, Rafael Nadal)\nTennisPlayer = DeclareSort(\"TennisPlayer\")  # Tennis players (Coco Gauff, Iga \u015awi\u0105tek, Rafael Nadal)\nEvent = DeclareSort(\"Event\")  # Events (Roland Garros 2022)\n\n# Define predicates\nRankedHighlyByWTA = Function(\"RankedHighlyByWTA\", Person, BoolSort())  # RankedHighlyByWTA(x)\nLostTo = Function(\"LostTo\", Person, Person, BoolSort())  # LostTo(x, y)\nIsMostActiveInMajorTennis = Function(\"IsMostActiveInMajorTennis\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsMostActiveInMajorTennis(x)\nIsFemale = Function(\"IsFemale\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsFemale(x)\nIsMale = Function(\"IsMale\", Person, BoolSort())  # IsMale(x)\nIsAt = Function(\"IsAt\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # IsAt(x, event)\nIsTennisPlayerAt = Function(\"IsTennisPlayerAt\", Person, Event, BoolSort())  # IsTennisPlayerAt(x, event)\n\n# Declare constants\nCoco_Gauff = Const(\"Coco_Gauff\", Person)\nIga_Swi\u0105tek = Const(\"Iga_Swi\u0105tek\", Person)\nRafael_Nadal = Const(\"Rafael_Nadal\", Person)\nRoland_Garros_2022 = Const(\"Roland_Garros_2022\", Event)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Person)\ny = Const(\"y\", Person)\nz = Const(\"z\", Person)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Implies(RankedHighlyByWTA(x), IsMostActiveInMajorTennis(x)))  # If x is ranked highly by WTA, then x is one of the most active players in major tennis\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(LostTo(x, Iga_Swi\u0105tek), RankedHighlyByWTA(x))))  # Everyone who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 is ranked highly by the Women's Tennis Association\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsAt(x, Roland_Garros_2022), And(IsFemale(x), LostTo(x, Iga_Swi\u0105tek))))  # All female tennis players at Roland Garros 2022 lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsTennisPlayerAt(x, Roland_Garros_2022), Or(IsFemale(x), IsMale(x))))  # All tennis players at Roland Garros in 2022 are either female or male\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(IsTennisPlayerAt(x, Roland_Garros_2022), LostTo(x, Rafael_Nadal))))  # All male tennis players at Roland Garros in 2022 lost to Rafael Nadal\nsolver.add(Or(RankedHighlyByWTA(Coco_Gauff), LostTo(Coco_Gauff, Rafael_Nadal)))  # Coco Gauff is ranked highly by the Women's Tennis Association or lost to Rafael Nadal\nsolver.add(IsAt(Coco_Gauff, Roland_Garros_2022))  # Coco Gauff is at Roland Garros 2022\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Not(And(LostTo(Coco_Gauff, Iga_Swi\u0105tek), IsMostActiveInMajorTennis(Coco_Gauff)))  # Coco Gauff is not both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: Coco Gauff is not both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Coco Gauff is both a player who lost to Iga \u015awi\u0105tek at Roland Garros 2022 and one of the most active players in major tennis. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    - (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: Some pets are cats. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions.         "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nMedia = DeclareSort(\"Media\")  # Media\nText = DeclareSort(\"Text\")  # Text\nService = DeclareSort(\"Service\")  # Service\nBook = DeclareSort(\"Book\")  # Book\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Digital = Function(\"Is_Digital\", Media, BoolSort())  # Digital(x)\nIs_Analog = Function(\"Is_Analog\", Media, BoolSort())  # Analog(x)\nIs_PrintedText = Function(\"Is_PrintedText\", Media, BoolSort())  # PrintedText(x)\nIs_HardcoverBook = Function(\"Is_HardcoverBook\", Media, BoolSort())  # HardcoverBook(x)\nIs_StreamingService = Function(\"Is_StreamingService\", Service, BoolSort())  # StreamingService(x)\n\n# Declare constants\nMedia_1984 = Const(\"Media_1984\", Media)\nService_1984 = Const(\"Service_1984\", Service)\nx = Const(\"x\", Media)\ny = Const(\"y\", Media)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Digital(x)))  # \u00acDigital(x)\nsolver.add(Is_Analog(x))  # Analog(x)\nsolver.add(Is_Digital(Service_1984))  # Digital(1984)\nsolver.add(Is_PrintedText(x))  # PrintedText(x)\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_HardcoverBook(x), Is_PrintedText(x)))  # HardcoverBook(x) \u2192 PrintedText(x)\nsolver.add(Implies(Is_StreamingService(Service_1984), Is_HardcoverBook(Media_1984)))  # StreamingService(1984) \u2192 HardcoverBook(1984)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Is_PrintedText(Media_1984)  # PrintedText(1984)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: 1984 is printed text. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: 1984 is not printed text. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

                "content": "You are an AI assistant that generates Python code for logical reasoning using the Z3 SMT solver. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency, correctness, and clarity in the generated code:\n\n1. **General Structure**\n  - **Use the Z3 SMT solver to encode First-Order Logic (FOL) problems.**\n  - **Define sorts (types) explicitly** to represent different domains (e.g., `Person`, `Object`).\n  - **Define predicates (functions returning Boolean values)** for logical relationships.\n  - **Declare constants for specific named entities** (e.g., `Theistic_God = Const(\"Theistic_God\", Person)`).\n  - **Declare variables (`x`, `y`, etc.) using `Const` BEFORE using them** in `ForAll` or `Exists` quantifiers.\n  - **Use quantifiers (`ForAll`, `Exists`)** to define universal and existential constraints.\n  - **Ensure logical constraints and premises are correctly encoded.**\n  - **Formulate the conclusion as a logical statement to be tested.**\n  - **Implement a two-step verification process:**\n    - **Step 1:** Test `Not(conclusion)` to check for counterexamples.\n    - **Step 2:** Test `conclusion` to verify direct satisfaction.\n  - **Classify the result as either True, False, or Uncertain** based on solver outcomes.\n\n2. **Code Formatting**\n   - **Imports**: Always use `from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Not, Or, BoolSort, Const` with explicitly imported functions.\n   - **Variable Naming**:\n     - Use **CamelCase** for sort names (e.g., `Person`, `School`).\n     - Use **snake_case** for function (predicate) names (e.g., `attended`, `located_in_UK`).\n     - Use **PascalCase** for constant entities (e.g., `William_Dickinson`, `Theistic_God`).\n     - Use **single-letter lowercase variables (`x`, `p`, `s`) for quantification**.\n   - **Declare Sorts & Constants Properly (Take Person as an example)**:\n     - Use DeclareSort(\"Person\") for domain types.\n     - Use Const(\"x\", Person) to declare individual variables (avoiding \"SortRef is not callable\" errors).\n     - Declare individual variables BEFORE use in ForAll or Exists.\n        - x = Const(\"x\", Person)\n        - y = Const(\"y\", Person)\n   - **Logical Expressions**:\n     - Use `ForAll([...], Implies(...))` for universal constraints.\n     - Use `Exists([...], And(...))` for existential constraints.\n     - Use `Not(...)` to negate logical statements.\n     - Notably, you mush define variables before using them.\n   - **Solver Handling**:\n     - Always use `solver.push()` before adding a test condition.\n     - Always use `solver.pop()` after a test condition to restore the original state.\n     - Convert solver results to strings (`str(solver.check())`) for comparison.\n   - **Result Interpretation**:\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily true.\n     - If `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"unsat\"`, the conclusion is necessarily false.\n     - If both `solver.check(Not(conclusion)) == \"sat\"` and `solver.check(conclusion) == \"sat\"`, the conclusion depends on missing assumptions.\n     - If an unexpected result occurs, print `\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\"`\n\n3. **Output Formatting**\n    -         "conclusions": "1984 is a streaming service.",
        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nObject = DeclareSort(\"Object\")  # Objects (1984, hardcover book, streaming service)\nMedia = DeclareSort(\"Media\")  # Media (analog media, digital media)\nText = DeclareSort(\"Text\")  # Text (printed text)\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_Digital = Function(\"Is_Digital\", Media, BoolSort())  # Digital(x)\nIs_Analog = Function(\"Is_Analog\", Media, BoolSort())  # Analog(x)\nIs_Printed = Function(\"Is_Printed\", Text, BoolSort())  # Printed(x)\nIs_Hardcover = Function(\"Is_Hardcover\", Object, BoolSort())  # Hardcover(x)\nIs_StreamingService = Function(\"Is_StreamingService\", Object, BoolSort())  # StreamingService(x)\n\n# Declare constants\n1984 = Const(\"1984\", Object)\nx = Const(\"x\", Object)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Digital(1984)))  # \u223cDigital(1984)\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Printed(x), Is_Analog(x))))  # \u2200x (Printed(x) \u2192 Analog(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_StreamingService(x), Is_Digital(x))))  # \u2200x (StreamingService(x) \u2192 Digital(x))\nsolver.add(ForAll([x], Implies(Is_Hardcover(x), Is_Printed(x))))  # \u2200x (Hardcover(x) \u2192 Printed(x))\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Is_StreamingService(1984)  # StreamingService(1984)\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: 1984 is a streaming service. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: 1984 is not a streaming service. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(result)",

        "rationale": "from z3 import Solver, DeclareSort, Function, ForAll, Exists, Implies, And, Or, Not, BoolSort, Const\n\n# Declare sorts\nLanguage = DeclareSort(\"Language\")  # Languages (Romance, Indo-European, etc.)\nFamily = DeclareSort(\"Family\")  # Language families (Romance languages, Indo-European, etc.)\nLanguageFamily = DeclareSort(\"LanguageFamily\")  # Language family (Romance, Indo-European, etc.)\nRelationship = DeclareSort(\"Relationship\")  # Relationship between languages\n\n# Define predicates\nIs_RomanceLanguage = Function(\"Is_RomanceLanguage\", Language, BoolSort())  # Romance(x)\nIs_IndoEuropean = Function(\"Is_IndoEuropean\", Language, BoolSort())  # IndoEuropean(x)\nIs_LanguageFamily = Function(\"Is_LanguageFamily\", Language, BoolSort())  # LanguageFamily(x)\nIs_Related = Function(\"Is_Related\", Language, Language, BoolSort())  # Related(x, y)\n\n# Declare constants\nFrench = Const(\"French\", Language)\nSpanish = Const(\"Spanish\", Language)\nGerman = Const(\"German\", Language)\nBasque = Const(\"Basque\", Language)\nRomance = Const(\"Romance\", LanguageFamily)\nIndoEuropean = Const(\"IndoEuropean\", LanguageFamily)\n\n# Declare variables\nx = Const(\"x\", Language)\ny = Const(\"y\", Language)\n\n# Define solver\nsolver = Solver()\n\n# **Premises**\nsolver.add(Is_RomanceLanguage(French))  # \u2200x Romance(x)\nsolver.add(Is_RomanceLanguage(Spanish))  # Romance(x)\nsolver.add(Is_LanguageFamily(Romance))  # LanguageFamily(x)\nsolver.add(Is_LanguageFamily(IndoEuropean))  # LanguageFamily(x)\nsolver.add(Is_Related(French, Spanish))  # Related(French, Spanish)\nsolver.add(Is_Related(German, Spanish))  # Related(German, Spanish)\nsolver.add(Not(Is_Related(Basque, x)))  # \u00acRelated(Basque, x)\n\n# **Conclusion to Check**\nconclusion = Is_RomanceLanguage(German)  # German is a Romance language\n\n# **Check validity**\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(Not(conclusion))  # Negate the conclusion and check for contradiction\nresult1 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\nsolver.push()\nsolver.add(conclusion)\nresult2 = solver.check()\nsolver.pop()\n\n# **Corrected Decision Logic**\nfrom z3 import unsat, sat\n\nif result1 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily true: German is a Romance language. (True)\")\n    result = 'True'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == unsat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is necessarily false: German is not a Romance language. (False)\")\n    result = 'False'\nelif result1 == sat and result2 == sat:\n    print(\"The conclusion is uncertain: It depends on additional unstated assumptions. (Uncertain)\")\n    result = 'Uncertain'\nelse:\n    print(\"Unexpected result, possible logical error.\")\n    result = 'Unknown'\n\nprint(\"The final answer is\", result)",
